{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17524562","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17524562"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:06:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:06:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14008"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14008","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14008"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.37,0.23,0.15,0.19,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6657"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108787"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6657","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6657"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14008"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91150"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"214"},{"type":"tags","id":"1149"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13669"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13670"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15307"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38411"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38479"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108787","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108787"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 74-year-old man presents with a painless swelling in the left side of his scrotum (Image). This has been present for about one year. As part of the physical examination, it should be determined whether this is a hydrocele or an inguino-scrotal hernia.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following physical signs would most reliably support the first of those two possible diagnoses?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Absence of a cough impulse","Absence of transillumination","Ability to feel the testis as a distinct entity","Clear and unobstructed palpation of the vas deferens","Enlargement of the swelling on standing"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe hydrocele is a common cause of scrotal swellings. Other important swellings to consider are inguino-scrotal hernias, testicular tumours and epididymal cysts. Hydroceles are usually very easy to diagnose on clinical grounds alone. This can be done on the basis of assessing whether or not the swelling is confined to the scrotum, whether it separate from the testis and whether the contents of the swelling are sufficiently clear to allow transillumination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe first part of the physical examination is an assessment of the normal side of the scrotum and its contents. The testis should be clearly palpable, as should be the vas deferens, as it ascends up into the inguinal canal. When examining the abnormal side the first action should be to try and get above the swelling. If this can be done and the \u003Cstrong\u003Evas deferens palpated clearly\u003C/strong\u003E, then the swelling arises from within the scrotum.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETransillumination can also be very helpful, but if the tunica vaginalis is thickened and the contents of the hydrocele, cloudy, then this physical sign may be absent. A cough impulse would be associated with an inguino-scrotal hernia, but is not always present in these hernias. If the swelling enlarges on standing, the swelling is more likely to be an inguino-scrotal hernia. If the testis can be felt as distinct entity, this means that the swelling is not a hydrocele, which would normally envelope it.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHydroceles can be primary or secondary. Primary hydroceles can be communicating or non-communicating and the degree of communication will depend on where the processus vaginalis has closed. The large majority of hydroceles will be secondary and have arisen to a recognisable pathological process (infection, trauma, malignancy) or - as in most cases - idiopathic.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most hydroceles in adults are idiopathic in nature and of limited clinical significance"],"references":["Hoang VT, Van HAT, Hoang TH, et al. A Review of Classification, Diagnosis, and Management of Hydrocele. J Ultrasound Med 2024; 43:599\u2013607."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91150"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14008"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20921"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20921","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20921"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ldynXNxrjbYsNvgdWVBqfRdzuwOiB5.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ldynXNxrjbYsNvgdWVBqfRdzuwOiB5.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1125}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91150","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91150"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-13T14:41:15+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-13T14:41:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6657"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108787"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":nul